# Multi-Platform Docker Image Builds

Build Docker images that run on multiple CPU architectures using `docker buildx`.

---

## Prerequisites

### Enable buildx

`buildx` is included with Docker Desktop by default. On Linux, verify it's available:

```bash
docker buildx version
```

### Create and use a builder instance

The default builder doesn't support multi-platform builds. Create one that does:

```bash
docker buildx create --name multiplatform-builder --use
docker buildx inspect --bootstrap
```

---

## Build Commands

### Single platform — linux/amd64

```bash
docker buildx build --platform linux/amd64 -t <your-image-name> .
```

### Multi-platform — amd64 + arm64

```bash
docker buildx build --platform linux/amd64,linux/arm64 -t <your-image-name> .
```

---

## Push to Registry

Multi-platform images must be pushed to a registry — they cannot be loaded into the local Docker daemon directly.

```bash
docker buildx build \
  --platform linux/amd64,linux/arm64 \
  -t <your-dockerhub-username>/<your-image-name>:<tag> \
  --push \
  .
```

### Load single-platform image locally (no push)

```bash
docker buildx build \
  --platform linux/amd64 \
  -t <your-image-name>:<tag> \
  --load \
  .
```

> `--load` only works with a single platform. Use `--push` for multi-platform.

---

## Verify the Image Manifest

After pushing, confirm both platforms are present:

```bash
docker buildx imagetools inspect <your-dockerhub-username>/<your-image-name>:<tag>
```

Expected output will show both:
```
Platform: linux/amd64
Platform: linux/arm64
```

---

## Common Platforms

| Platform | Use case |
|---|---|
| `linux/amd64` | Standard cloud VMs, most CI runners |
| `linux/arm64` | Apple Silicon (M1/M2), AWS Graviton, Raspberry Pi 4 |
| `linux/arm/v7` | Raspberry Pi 3 and older ARM devices |

---

## Notes

- Multi-platform builds use QEMU emulation for cross-architecture compilation — builds may be slower than native
- Always tag images with a version (`v1.0.0`) in addition to `latest`
- If your base image doesn't support a platform, the build will fail — check the base image manifest first
